          <br>
          Please read it fully before our Saturday session. <b>From the
            date of this mail, v2 is the operative guide for all FSD
            documentation work in SPINRISE. </b>V1 is superseded.<br>
          <br>
          <b><font size="4">Why v2 exists<br>
            </font></b><br>
          Version 2 was built entirely from what you told me.<br>
          <br>
          Three of you responded to my v1 circulation mail with
          observations that were technically sharp and practically
          important. I want to acknowledge each contribution by name,
          because the team should know where v2 came from.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Sathishkumar </b>pointed out that the Kalsofte ERP
          distributes business logic across Common modules, Class
          modules, and stored procedures — not just the .frm file. He
          also highlighted that the TC (Transaction Code) framework,
          which drives stock direction and accounting entries across
          most of our modules, is largely implemented inside stored
          procedures and would be missed entirely if only the form code
          was submitted to Claude.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Mariyaiya </b>raised a more fundamental concern: that
          several PR, PO, and Service PO screens have pending customer
          customisations in various stages of stability. Submitting
          unstabilised code to Claude would produce an FSD that
          documents an incomplete version of the screen — and that
          instability would be permanently carried into SPINRISE.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Mariyaiya then went further.</b> Before I could even
          respond, he produced a detailed critical analysis of the
          Purchase Requisition form (tmpPoindent.frm) — a 9,108-line VB6
          form — and shared it with Muthuvel for IST review. That
          document, which I have gone through in detail, identified 3
          Critical defects, 3 High issues, 4 Medium issues, and 2 Low
          issues in the form code. It also proposed the four-category
          validation structure, the error message catalogue, the summary
          scorecard, and the customer variation register — all of which
          are now standard sections in the v2 FSD template.<br>
          <br>
          This is what good teamwork looks like. You were given a guide,
          you used it on a real form, you found its limits, and you
          reported back with precision. V2 is the direct result.<br>
          <br>
          <b><font size="4">What is new in v2<br>
            </font></b><br>
          For those who have read v1, here is what changed:<br>
          <br>
          Stage 0 is an entirely new mandatory phase that must be
          completed before any FSD documentation begins. It covers code
          stabilisation review, the screen readiness checklist, what to
          collect before opening Claude (no longer just the .frm file —
          now includes Common modules, Class modules, and all stored
          procedures), the TC framework reference table, the customer
          variation register, and the dead code identification step.
          Stage 0 is not optional. No FSD work begins on any screen
          until Stage 0 is complete and TL-Dev has signed off.<br>
          <br>
          The follow-up prompts grew from three to six. Three new
          prompts were added: one for Common and Class module logic, one
          for stored procedure business rules, and one specifically for
          TC framework documentation. These address the gap our first VB
          developer identified.<br>
          <br>
          The FSD template expanded from 8 sections to 14 sections. The
          six new sections are the TC Framework, Common and Class Module
          Dependencies, Error Message Catalogue, Customer Variation
          Register, SPINRISE Migration Recommendations, and the Summary
          Scorecard. All six are mandatory for transaction screens.<br>
          <br>
          The review chain is updated to four levels with the full IST
          structured questionnaire (IST-1 to IST-7) that every Module Sr
          IST Member must answer for each form they review.<br>
          <br>
          A new Section 8 documents eight known defect patterns to
          actively search for in every VB6 form before submitting to
          Claude: application-terminating End statements, hardcoded
          customer IDs, SQL string concatenation, dead code blocks,
          inconsistent duplicate logic, hardcoded file paths, missing
          transaction rollback, and typos in error messages. Each
          pattern has the code signature to search for and the action to
          take.<br>
          <br>
          Three quick reference cards are now at the back: the Developer
          Daily Card, the four-column Reviewer Checklist, and the new
          Defect Patterns Card. Print all three and keep them at your
          desk.<br>
          <br>
          <b>How I need each of you to use this guide<br>
          </b><br>
          <b>Module VB Developers:</b><br>
          Section 3 (Stage 0) and Section 4 (the six steps and six
          prompts) are your primary reference. Read them in full. Before
          you begin any FSD, complete Stage 0 for that screen. Do not
          skip the Customer Variation Register. Do not submit dead code.
          Run all six follow-up prompts, not just the ones you feel are
          relevant.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Module Sr IST Members:</b><br>
          Section 6, Level 1 and the IST Structured Questionnaire
          (questions IST-1 to IST-7) are your reference. For every FSD
          you review, answer all seven questions. Section 8 (the defect
          patterns) is also important for you — you are the person most
          likely to know from site experience whether an
          application-terminating behaviour or a hardcoded customer
          variation has caused problems in practice.<br>
          <br>
          <b>TL-IST:</b><br>
          Section 6, Level 2. Your role is cross-module consistency. Pay
          particular attention to whether TC framework values and stored
          procedure business rules are consistent with how the same
          logic is handled in other modules you have implemented.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Project Manager:</b><br>
          Section 6, Level 3. Before any FSD reaches the CEO, confirm
          that all 14 sections are complete, all IST questions are
          answered, the customer variation register is filled, and the
          summary scorecard is present. An incomplete FSD must be
          returned to the developer, not passed forward.<br>
          <br>
          <b>New Developer (Abinandan):</b><br>
          Welcome again. This guide is your primary reference for how
          SPINRISE development works. Start by reading Section 3 (Stage
          0) and Section 4. The defect patterns in Section 8 will be
          particularly useful as you begin reading Kalsofte VB6 code for
          the first time — you will encounter all of these patterns. Now
          you know what to do with each one.<br>
          <br>
          <b>Jr Web Dev team:</b><br>
          Section 4, Step 6 and Section 7 are your references. The
          approved FSD is your specification for React UI generation.
          Read Section 7 carefully — it shows you exactly what prompt to
          use when an FSD is handed to you for code conversion.<br>
          <br>
          <b><font size="4">A word on how we got here</font></b><br>
          <br>
          When I shared v1, I said: this is version 1, your feedback
          will shape version 2. You delivered. In less than a week, the
          team produced two substantive pieces of written feedback and
          one detailed 12-section critical analysis of a real form. That
          is not normal. Most teams wait to be asked.<br>
          <br>
          <b>The quality of SPINRISE depends on the quality of our FSDs.</b>
          The quality of our FSDs depends on the rigour of our process.
          The rigour of our process depends on each of you taking
          ownership of the part only you can contribute — your domain
          knowledge, your site experience, your module expertise.<br>
          <br>
          V2 reflects all of that. Bring the same energy to v2 that
          produced it.<br>
          <br>
          <b><font size="4">What I need from you </font></b><br>
          <br>
          Every developer and IST member: have read v2 in full.<br>
          <br>
          Module VB Developers: bring your Stage 0 readiness assessment
